16 module forpy_mod
17 !! author: Elias Rabel
18 !!
19 !! Forpy: A library for Fortran-Python interoperability.
20 !!
21 !! Forpy allows you to use Python features within Fortran ("Python in Fortran")
22 !! For example: Python modules, datastructures such as list, dict, tuple
23 !! Furthermore you can write Python (extension) modules in Fortran ("Fortran in Python")
24 
25 ! Contact:
26 ! Let me know, if you find this library useful:
27 ! Mail: ylikx.0 at gmail dot com
28 ! Web: https://github.com/ylikx
29 
30 ! This project uses the fypp preprocessor (https://github.com/aradi/fypp)
31 ! to generate the code
32 ! Do not edit forpy_mod.F90, edit forpy_mod.fypp
33 !
34 
35 #ifdef PYTHON2_32
36 #define PYTHON2
37 #endif
38

1980 function forpy_initialize(use_numpy) result(ierror)
1981 
1982  logical, optional, intent(in) :: use_numpy
1983  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
1984 
1985  logical :: numpy_flag
1986 
1987  if (present(use_numpy)) then
1988  numpy_flag = use_numpy
1989  else
1990  numpy_flag = .true.
1991  endif
1992 
1993  ierror = 1_c_int
1994  if (py_isinitialized() == 0_c_int) then
1995  call py_initialize()
1996  endif
1997 
1998  ierror = 0_c_int
1999  if (global_forpy_initialized == 0) then
2000  ierror = forpy_initialize_forpy_globals()
2001  if (ierror == 0_c_int) then
2002  global_forpy_initialized = 1
2003  endif
2004  endif
2005 
2006  if (ierror == 0_c_int .and. numpy_flag &
2007  .and. .not. c_associated(global_numpy_mod)) then
2008  ierror = forpy_initialize_numpy()
2009  endif
2010 end function
2011 
2012 function forpy_initialize_forpy_globals() result(ierror)
2013  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
2014 
2015  ! Initialise Python's None object
2016  ierror = forpy_initialize_none()
2017  if (ierror /= 0) then
2018  return
2019  endif
2020 
2021  ierror = forpy_initialize_float()
2022  if (ierror /= 0) then
2023  return
2024  endif
2025 
2026  ierror = forpy_initialize_complex()
2027  if (ierror /= 0) then
2028  return
2029  endif
2030 
2031  ierror = forpy_initialize_bool()
2032  if (ierror /= 0) then
2033  return
2034  endif
2035 
2036  ierror = forpy_initialize_unicode()
2037  if (ierror /= 0) then
2038  return
2039  endif
2040 
2041  ierror = forpy_initialize_exceptions()
2042  if (ierror /= 0) then
2043  return
2044  endif
2045 
2046  ierror = forpy_initialize_sys_argv()
2047  if (ierror /= 0) then
2048  return
2049  endif
2050 end function

2055 function forpy_initialize_sys_argv() result(ierror)
2056  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
2057 
2058  ! there also exist C-API functions to set sys.argv, but they involve wchar_t
2059  ! which iso_c_binding does not support and that has platform dep. size
2060  ierror = pyrun_simplestring(import sys" // C_NEW_LINE // &
2061  "if not hasattr(sys, 'argv') or sys.argv==[]:" // C_NEW_LINE // &
2062  " sys.argv=['']" // C_NEW_LINE // C_NULL_CHAR)
2063 end function

2065 function forpy_initialize_numpy() result(ierror)
2066  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
2067 
2068  type(c_ptr) :: asarray_str
2069  type(c_ptr) :: ndarray_str
2070 
2071  ! Initialisation of Numpy
2072  global_numpy_mod = PyImport_ImportModule(C_CHAR_"numpy" // C_NULL_CHAR)
2073 .not. if ( c_associated(global_numpy_mod)) then
2074  ierror = NO_NUMPY_ERROR
2075  call err_clear
2076  return
2077  else
2078 
2079  ! TODO: exception checks?
2080  ierror = box_value(asarray_str, "asarray")
2081 
2082 .not. if ( c_associated(asarray_str)) then
2083  ierror = NO_NUMPY_ERROR
2084  call err_clear
2085  return
2086  else
2087  global_numpy_asarray_method = PyObject_GetAttr(global_numpy_mod, asarray_str)
2088  call Py_Decref(asarray_str)
2089 
2090 .not. if ( c_associated(global_numpy_asarray_method)) then
2091  ierror = NO_NUMPY_ERROR ! Something's wrong with numpy... but might use Python without numpy
2092  call err_clear
2093  endif
2094  endif
2095  endif
2096 
2097  ! Get the numpy.ndarray type-object
2098  if (ierror == 0) then
2099  ierror = box_value(ndarray_str, "ndarray")
2100 
2101  if (ierror /= 0) then
2102  return
2103  endif
2104 
2105  global_numpy_ndarray_typeobj = PyObject_GetAttr(global_numpy_mod, ndarray_str)
2106  call Py_Decref(ndarray_str)
2107 
2108 .not. if ( c_associated(global_numpy_asarray_method)) then
2109  ierror = NO_NUMPY_ERROR ! No Numpy...
2110  call err_clear
2111  endif
2112 
2113  endif
2114 
2115 end function
2116 
2117 ! sets up Python's None
2118 function forpy_initialize_none() result(ierror)
2119  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
2120 
2121  type(list) :: li
2122  type(tuple) :: args
2123  type(dict) :: kwargs
2124  type(object) :: none_obj
2125 
2126  ! A bit hacky: use return value of the following python expression
2127  ! to get pointer to the singleton None-object (_Py_NoneStruct):
2128  ! The expression is: [].sort()
2129 
2130  ierror = list_create(li)
2131  if (ierror /= 0) then
2132  return
2133  endif
2134 
2135  ierror = tuple_create(args, 0)
2136  if (ierror /= 0) then
2137  call li%destroy()
2138  return
2139  endif
2140 
2141  ierror = dict_create(kwargs)
2142  if (ierror /= 0) then
2143  call li%destroy()
2144  call args%destroy()
2145  return
2146  endif
2147 
2148  ierror = call_py_attribute(none_obj, li, "sort", args, kwargs)
2149 
2150 .and. if (ierror == 0 c_associated(none_obj%py_object)) then
2151  global_Py_NoneStruct_ptr = none_obj%py_object
2152  call none_obj%destroy()
2153  endif
2154 
2155  call li%destroy()
2156  call args%destroy()
2157  call kwargs%destroy()
2158 
2159  ierror = 0_C_INT
2160 end function
2161 
2162 ! Get pointer to "float"-type object
2163 function forpy_initialize_float() result(ierror)
2164  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
2165 
2166  type(c_ptr) :: a_float
2167  type(PyObject), pointer :: ptr
2168 
2169  a_float = PyFloat_FromDouble(1.0_C_DOUBLE)
2170 
2171 .not. if ( c_associated(a_float)) then
2172  ierror = EXCEPTION_ERROR
2173  return
2174  endif
2175 
2176  call c_f_pointer(a_float, ptr)
2177  global_pyfloat_type_ptr = ptr%ob_type
2178  call Py_DecRef(a_float)
2179  ierror = 0_C_INT
2180 end function
2181 
2182 ! Get pointer to "complex"-type object
2183 ! Note: floats are not complex in Python
2184 function forpy_initialize_complex() result(ierror)
2185  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
2186 
2187  type(c_ptr) :: a_complex
2188  type(PyObject), pointer :: ptr
2189 
2190  a_complex = PyComplex_FromDoubles(1.0_C_DOUBLE, 1.0_C_DOUBLE)
2191 
2192 .not. if ( c_associated(a_complex)) then
2193  ierror = EXCEPTION_ERROR
2194  return
2195  endif
2196 
2197  call c_f_pointer(a_complex, ptr)
2198  global_pycomplex_type_ptr = ptr%ob_type
2199  call Py_DecRef(a_complex)
2200  ierror = 0_C_INT
2201 end function
2202 
2203 ! Get pointer to "unicode"-type object
2204 function forpy_initialize_unicode() result(ierror)
2205  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
2206 
2207  type(c_ptr) :: a_unicode
2208  type(PyObject), pointer :: ptr
2209 
2210  character(kind=C_CHAR), dimension(1) :: a
2211  character(kind=C_CHAR), dimension(7) :: b
2212 
2213  a = [C_NULL_CHAR]
2214  b = ['s','t','r','i','c','t', C_NULL_CHAR]
2215 
2216  ! fix for PGI compiler: pgi does not like if a and b are
2217  ! string literals in this function call
2218  a_unicode = PyUnicode_DecodeUTF8(a, 0_PY_SSIZE_T_KIND, b)
2219 
2220 .not. if ( c_associated(a_unicode)) then
2221  ierror = EXCEPTION_ERROR
2222  return
2223  endif
2224 
2225  call c_f_pointer(a_unicode, ptr)
2226  global_pyunicode_type_ptr = ptr%ob_type
2227  call Py_DecRef(a_unicode)
2228  ierror = 0_C_INT
2229 end function
2230 
2231 ! Get pointer to "bool"-type object and the singletons Py_True and Py_False
2232 function forpy_initialize_bool() result(ierror)
2233  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
2234 
2235  type(c_ptr) :: a_bool
2236  type(PyObject), pointer :: ptr
2237 
2238  a_bool = PyBool_FromLong(0_C_LONG)
2239 
2240 .not. if ( c_associated(a_bool)) then
2241  ierror = EXCEPTION_ERROR
2242  return
2243  endif
2244 
2245  call c_f_pointer(a_bool, ptr)
2246  global_pybool_type_ptr = ptr%ob_type
2247  global_Py_FalseStruct_ptr = a_bool
2248  call Py_DecRef(a_bool)
2249 
2250  a_bool = PyBool_FromLong(1_C_LONG)
2251 
2252 .not. if ( c_associated(a_bool)) then
2253  ierror = EXCEPTION_ERROR
2254  return
2255  endif
2256 
2257  global_Py_TrueStruct_ptr = a_bool
2258  call Py_DecRef(a_bool)
2259 
2260  ierror = 0_C_INT
2261 end function

2424 !> Frees resources used by Python interpreter. Call when finished using forpy.
2425 subroutine forpy_finalize()
2426  global_forpy_initialized = 0
2427  call Py_Decref(global_numpy_asarray_method)
2428  call Py_Decref(global_numpy_mod)
2429  global_numpy_asarray_method = C_NULL_PTR
2430  global_numpy_mod = C_NULL_PTR
2431 
2432  call Py_Finalize()
2433 end subroutine

2436 !-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
2437 ! Functions to check type
2438 !> Checks if object is a Python long.
2439 logical function is_long(obj)
2440  !> The object to check.
2441  class(object), intent(in) :: obj
2442 
2443  is_long = (check_tp_flags(obj%py_object, ishft(1_C_LONG, 24)) /= 0)
2444 end function
2445 
2446 !> Checks if object is a Python list.
2447 logical function is_list(obj)
2448  !> The object to check.
2449  class(object), intent(in) :: obj
2450 
2451  is_list = (check_tp_flags(obj%py_object, ishft(1_C_LONG, 25)) /= 0)
2452 end function
2453 
2454 !> Checks if object is a Python tuple.
2455 logical function is_tuple(obj)
2456  !> The object to check.
2457  class(object), intent(in) :: obj
2458 
2459  is_tuple = (check_tp_flags(obj%py_object, ishft(1_C_LONG, 26)) /= 0)

2479 !> Checks if object is a Python float.
2480 logical function is_float(obj)
2481  !> The object to check.
2482  class(object), intent(in) :: obj
2483  type(PyObject), pointer :: obj_ptr
2484 
2485 .not..and. if ( (c_associated(obj%py_object) c_associated(global_pyfloat_type_ptr))) then
2486  is_float = .false.
2487  return
2488  endif
2489 
2490  call c_f_pointer(obj%py_object, obj_ptr)
2491  is_float = c_associated(global_pyfloat_type_ptr, obj_ptr%ob_type)
2492 .not. if ( is_float) then
2493  is_float = (PyType_IsSubtype(obj_ptr%ob_type, global_pyfloat_type_ptr) /= 0) ! Check if subtype
2494  endif
2495 end function

2607 
2608 !> Checks if object is a Numpy array.
2609 logical function is_ndarray(obj)
2610  !> The object to check.
2611  class(object), intent(in) :: obj
2612 
2613  integer(kind=C_INT) :: res
2614  type(c_ptr) :: err_obj
2615 
2616 .not. if ( c_associated(global_numpy_ndarray_typeobj)) then
2617  is_ndarray = .false.
2618  return
2619  endif
2620 
2621  res = PyObject_IsInstance(obj%py_object, global_numpy_ndarray_typeobj)
2622 
2623  ! if res==-1 then exception is set by PyObject_IsInstance
2624  ! clear the exception and return false
2625  if (res == -1_C_INT) then
2626  is_ndarray = .false.
2627  err_obj = PyErr_Occurred()
2628  if (c_associated(err_obj)) then
2629  call PyErr_Clear()
2630  endif
2631  return
2632  endif
2633 
2634  is_ndarray = (res == 1)
2635 end function
2636 
2637 !> Helper for type checks
2638 function check_tp_flags(py_obj, mask) result(res)
2639  type(c_ptr), intent(in) :: py_obj
2640  integer(kind=C_LONG), intent(in) :: mask
2641  integer(kind=C_LONG) :: res
2642 
2643  type(PyObject), pointer :: obj_ptr
2644  type(PyTypeObject), pointer :: type_ptr
2645 
2646  call c_f_pointer(py_obj, obj_ptr)
2647  call c_f_pointer(obj_ptr%ob_type, type_ptr)
2648 
2649  res = iand(type_ptr%tp_flags, mask)
2650 end function

3629 function sequence_contains(self, contain_flag, item) result(ierror)
3630  class(sequence), intent(in) :: self
3631  logical, intent(out) :: contain_flag
3632  class(object), intent(in) :: item
3633  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
3634 
3635  ! returns -1 on error, 0 if item not contained, 1 if contained
3636  ierror = PySequence_Contains(self%py_object, item%py_object)
3637  contain_flag = (ierror == 1_C_INT)
3638 
3639  if (contain_flag) then
3640  ierror = 0_C_INT
3641  endif
3642 
3643 end function

3998 
3999 ! See also: http://stackoverflow.com/questions/6111843/limitations-of-pytuple-setitem
4000 ! Tuple ref-count must be 1 - otherwise cannot set items
4001 function tuple_setitem_int32_int32(self, ind, item) result(ierror)
4002  class(tuple), intent(inout) :: self
4003  integer(kind=int32), intent(in) :: ind
4004  integer(kind=int32), intent(in) :: item
4005  integer(kind=C_INT):: ierror
4006 
4007  type(c_ptr) :: item_py
4008  integer(kind=PY_SSIZE_T_KIND) :: ind_py_ssize_t
4009 
4010  ierror = box_value(item_py, item)
4011  ind_py_ssize_t = int(ind, PY_SSIZE_T_KIND)
4012 
4013  !tuple: must use PyTuple_SetItem
4014  !PyTuple_SetItem steals a reference - in contrast to PyObject_SetItem
4015  if (ierror == 0) then
4016  ierror = PyTuple_SetItem(self%py_object, ind_py_ssize_t, item_py)
4017  ! note: no need for Py_DecRef since reference is stolen
4018  endif
4019 end function

4185  integer(kind=C_INT):: ierror
4186 
4187  type(c_ptr) :: item_py
4188  integer(kind=PY_SSIZE_T_KIND) :: ind_py_ssize_t
4189 
4190  ierror = box_value(item_py, item)
4191  ind_py_ssize_t = int(ind, PY_SSIZE_T_KIND)
4192 
4193  !tuple: must use PyTuple_SetItem
4194  !PyTuple_SetItem steals a reference - in contrast to PyObject_SetItem
4195  if (ierror == 0) then
4196  ierror = PyTuple_SetItem(self%py_object, ind_py_ssize_t, item_py)
4197  ! note: no need for Py_DecRef since reference is stolen
4198  endif
4199 end function

4401 function tuple_add(self, result_tuple, tuple_to_concatenate) result(ierror)
4402  class(tuple), intent(inout) :: self
4403  type(tuple), intent(out) :: result_tuple
4404  class(tuple), intent(inout) :: tuple_to_concatenate
4405  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
4406 
4407  ierror = 0_C_INT
4408  result_tuple%py_object = PySequence_Concat(self%py_object, tuple_to_concatenate%py_object)
4409 .not. if ( c_associated(result_tuple%py_object)) then
4410  ierror = EXCEPTION_ERROR
4411  endif

4414 function object_getattribute(self, attr, attr_name) result(ierror)
4415  class(object), intent(in) :: self
4416  type(object), intent(out) :: attr
4417  character(kind=C_CHAR, len=*), intent(in) :: attr_name
4418  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
4419 
4420  type(c_ptr) :: attr_name_str
4421 
4422  ierror = box_value(attr_name_str, attr_name)
4423 
4424  if (ierror == 0_C_INT) then
4425  attr%py_object = PyObject_GetAttr(self%py_object, attr_name_str)
4426  else
4427  return
4428  endif
4429 
4430  call Py_Decref(attr_name_str)
4431 
4432 .not. if ( c_associated(attr%py_object)) then
4433  ierror = EXCEPTION_ERROR
4434  endif
4435 end function
4436 
4437 function object_setattr(self, attr_name, attr_value) result(ierror)
4438  class(object), intent(inout) :: self
4439  character(kind=C_CHAR, len=*), intent(in) :: attr_name
4440  class(object), intent(in) :: attr_value
4441  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
4442 
4443  type(c_ptr) :: attr_name_str
4444 
4445  ierror = box_value(attr_name_str, attr_name)
4446 
4447  if (ierror == 0_C_INT) then
4448  ierror = PyObject_SetAttr(self%py_object, attr_name_str, attr_value%py_object)
4449  call Py_Decref(attr_name_str)
4450  endif
4451 end function
4452 
4453 function object_delattr(self, attr_name) result(ierror)
4454  class(object), intent(inout) :: self
4455  character(kind=C_CHAR, len=*), intent(in) :: attr_name
4456  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
4457 
4458  type(c_ptr) :: attr_name_str
4459  ierror = box_value(attr_name_str, attr_name)
4460 
4461  if (ierror == 0_C_INT) then
4462  ierror = PyObject_SetAttr(self%py_object, attr_name_str, C_NULL_PTR)
4463  call Py_Decref(attr_name_str)
4464  endif
4465 end function

4471  r = self%py_object
4472 end function

6104  if (ierror == 0_C_INT) then
6105  ierror = box_value(item_py, item)
6106 
6107  if (ierror /= 0) then
6108  call Py_DecRef(ind_py)
6109  return
6110  endif
6111  endif
6112 
6113  if (ierror == 0_C_INT) then
6114  ierror = PyObject_SetItem(self%py_object, ind_py, item_py)
6115  call Py_DecRef(item_py)
6116  call Py_DecRef(ind_py)
6117  endif
6118 
6119 end function
6120 
6121 
6122 function mapping_contains(self, contain_flag, item) result(ierror)
6123  class(Mapping), intent(in) :: self
6124  logical, intent(out) :: contain_flag
6125  class(object), intent(in) :: item
6126  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
6127 
6128  integer(kind=C_INT) :: cont
6129  ierror = 0_C_INT
6130  ! returns 0 if item not contained, 1 if contained
6131  ! in contrast to PySequence_Contains this never fails
6132  ! we want to have the same call signature as with sequence objects
6133  ! therefore we have ierror=0 as return value
6134  cont = PyMapping_HasKey(self%py_object, item%py_object)
6135  contain_flag = (cont == 1_C_INT)
6136 
6137 end function
6138

6143  class(object), intent(in) :: default_value
6144 
6145  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
6146 
6147  ierror = dict_get_helper(self, item%py_object, key%py_object, default_value%py_object, .false.)
6148 
6149 end function

6728 .and. if (c_associated(item_ptr) ierror == 0_C_INT) then
6729  ierror = unbox_value(item, item_ptr)
6730  call Py_Decref(item_ptr)
6731  else
6732  item = default_value
6733  endif
6734 
6735  call Py_Decref(key_ptr)
6736 
6737 end function

6929 function dict_setdefault_object_object(self, the_value, key, default_value) result(ierror)
6930  class(dict), intent(inout) :: self
6931  !> The value retrieved from the dict.
6932  type(object), intent(out) :: the_value
6933  !> Key to retrieve value from.
6934  class(object), intent(in) :: key
6935  !> Default value that is inserted into dict and returned., if key is not present.
6936  class(object), intent(in) :: default_value
6937  !> Error code, 0 on success
6938  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
6939 
6940  ierror = dict_get_helper(self, the_value%py_object, key%py_object, default_value%py_object, .true.)
6941 
6942 end function
6943 
6944 function dict_get_helper(self, item_ptr, key_ptr, default_value_ptr, setdefault) result(ierror)
6945  class(dict), intent(inout) :: self
6946  type(c_ptr), intent(out) :: item_ptr
6947  type(c_ptr), intent(in) :: key_ptr
6948  type(c_ptr), intent(in) :: default_value_ptr
6949  logical, intent(in) :: setdefault
6950  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
6951 
6952  ierror = 0_C_INT
6953  item_ptr = PyObject_GetItem(self%py_object, key_ptr)
6954 
6955 .not. if ( c_associated(item_ptr)) then
6956  !always return default value, when lookup fails
6957  item_ptr = default_value_ptr
6958  call Py_IncRef(default_value_ptr)
6959 
6960  if (exception_matches(KeyError)) then
6961  call err_clear()
6962 
6963  if (setdefault) then
6964  ierror = PyObject_SetItem(self%py_object, key_ptr, default_value_ptr)
6965  endif
6966  else
6967  ierror = EXCEPTION_ERROR
6968  return
6969  endif
6970  endif
6971 end function
6972 
6973 function dict_get_helper2(self, item_ptr, key_ptr) result(ierror)
6974  class(dict), intent(inout) :: self
6975  type(c_ptr), intent(out) :: item_ptr
6976  type(c_ptr), intent(in) :: key_ptr
6977  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
6978 
6979  ierror = 0_C_INT
6980  item_ptr = PyObject_GetItem(self%py_object, key_ptr)
6981 
6982 .not. if ( c_associated(item_ptr)) then
6983  if (exception_matches(KeyError)) then
6984  call err_clear()
6985  else
6986  ierror = EXCEPTION_ERROR
6987  return
6988  endif
6989  endif
6990 end function

7063 !-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
7064 Import a python module.!>
7065 !>
7066 !> Module must be in Python module search path.
7067 !> The search path can be set via the environment variable PYTHONPATH or by
7068 !> manipulating the list of paths retrieved by using [[get_sys_path]].
7069 function import_py(mod_py, mod_name) result(ierror)
7070  !> The imported module
7071  type(module_py), intent(out) :: mod_py
7072  !> Name of the module to import. Name can include dots "."
7073  character(kind=C_CHAR, len=*), intent(in) :: mod_name
7074  !> Error code, 0 on success.
7075  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
7076 
7077  ierror = 0_C_INT
7078  mod_py%py_object = PyImport_ImportModule(trim(mod_name) // C_NULL_CHAR)
7079 
7080 .not. if ( c_associated(mod_py%py_object)) then
7081  ierror = EXCEPTION_ERROR
7082  endif
7083 end function
7084 
7085 !-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
7086 !> Calling an object (method, function...) that is a member of another Python object (module,...).
7087 !>
7088 !> Python equivalent: return_value = obj.attr_name(*args, **kwargs)
7089 function call_py_attribute(return_value, obj, attr_name, args, kwargs) result(ierror)
7090  type(object), intent(out) :: return_value
7091  class(object), intent(in) :: obj
7092  character(kind=C_CHAR, len=*), intent(in) :: attr_name
7093  class(tuple), intent(in), optional :: args
7094  class(dict), intent(in), optional :: kwargs
7095 
7096  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
7097 
7098  type(object) :: obj_to_call
7099  ierror = obj%getattribute(obj_to_call, attr_name)
7100 
7101  if (ierror == 0) then
7102 
7103 .and. if (present(kwargs) present(args)) then
7104  ierror = call_py_object(return_value, obj_to_call, args, kwargs)
7105  elseif (present(args)) then
7106  ierror = call_py_object_nokwargs(return_value, obj_to_call, args)
7107  elseif (present(kwargs)) then
7108  ierror = call_py_object_only_kwargs(return_value, obj_to_call, kwargs)
7109  else
7110  ierror = call_py_object_noargs(return_value, obj_to_call)
7111  endif
7112 
7113  call obj_to_call%destroy()
7114  endif
7115 end function
7116 
7117 !> Calling a Python object (method, function...).
7118 !>
7119 !> Python equivalent: return_value = obj_to_call(*args, **kwargs)
7120 function call_py_object(return_value, obj_to_call, args, kwargs) result(ierror)
7121  type(object), intent(out) :: return_value
7122  class(object), intent(in) :: obj_to_call
7123  class(tuple), intent(in):: args
7124  class(dict), intent(in) :: kwargs
7125 
7126  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
7127 
7128  type(c_ptr) :: kw, args_ptr
7129 
7130  ierror = 0_C_INT
7131 
7132  kw = kwargs%py_object
7133  args_ptr = args%py_object
7134 
7135  return_value%py_object = PyObject_Call(obj_to_call%py_object, args_ptr, kw)
7136 
7137 .not. if ( c_associated(return_value%py_object)) then
7138  ierror = EXCEPTION_ERROR
7139  endif
7140 
7141 end function
7142 
7143 !> Python equivalent: return_value = obj_to_call(*args)
7144 function call_py_object_nokwargs(return_value, obj_to_call, args) result(ierror)
7145  type(object), intent(out) :: return_value
7146  class(object), intent(in) :: obj_to_call
7147  class(tuple), intent(in):: args
7148 
7149  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
7150  type(dict) :: kwargs
7151 
7152  ierror = dict_create(kwargs)
7153  if (ierror == 0) then
7154  ierror = call_py_object(return_value, obj_to_call, args, kwargs)
7155  call kwargs%destroy
7156  endif
7157 end function
7158 
7159 !> Python equivalent: return_value = obj_to_call()
7160 function call_py_object_noargs(return_value, obj_to_call) result(ierror)
7161  type(object), intent(out) :: return_value
7162  class(object), intent(in) :: obj_to_call
7163 
7164  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
7165  type(tuple) :: args
7166 
7167  ierror = tuple_create(args, 0)
7168  if (ierror == 0) then
7169  ierror = call_py_object_nokwargs(return_value, obj_to_call, args)
7170  call args%destroy
7171  endif
7172 end function
7173 
7174 !> Python equivalent: return_value = obj_to_call(**kwargs)
7175 function call_py_object_only_kwargs(return_value, obj_to_call, kwargs) result(ierror)
7176  type(object), intent(out) :: return_value
7177  class(object), intent(in) :: obj_to_call
7178  class(dict), intent(in) :: kwargs
7179 
7180  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
7181  type(tuple) :: args
7182 
7183  ierror = tuple_create(args, 0)
7184  if (ierror == 0) then
7185  ierror = call_py_object(return_value, obj_to_call, args, kwargs)
7186  call args%destroy
7187  endif
7188 end function
7189 
7190 !> Python equivalent: obj.attr_name(*args, **kwargs)
7191 function call_py_noret_attribute(obj, attr_name, args, kwargs) result(ierror)
7192  class(object), intent(in) :: obj
7193  character(kind=C_CHAR, len=*), intent(in) :: attr_name
7194  class(tuple), intent(in), optional :: args
7195  class(dict), intent(in), optional :: kwargs
7196 
7197  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
7198  type(object) :: return_value
7199 
7200 .and. if (present(kwargs) present(args)) then
7201  ierror = call_py(return_value, obj, attr_name, args, kwargs)
7202  elseif (present(args)) then
7203  ierror = call_py(return_value, obj, attr_name, args)
7204  elseif (present(kwargs)) then
7205  ierror = call_py(return_value, obj, attr_name, kwargs=kwargs)
7206  else
7207  ierror = call_py(return_value, obj, attr_name)
7208  endif
7209 
7210  call return_value%destroy
7211 
7212 end function
7213 
7214 !> Python equivalent: obj.attr_name(*args, **kwargs)
7215 function call_py_noret_object(obj_to_call, args, kwargs) result(ierror)
7216  class(object), intent(in) :: obj_to_call
7217  class(tuple), intent(in), optional :: args
7218  class(dict), intent(in), optional :: kwargs
7219 
7220  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
7221  type(object) :: return_value
7222 
7223 .and. if (present(kwargs) present(args)) then
7224  ierror = call_py(return_value, obj_to_call, args, kwargs)
7225  elseif (present(args)) then
7226  ierror = call_py(return_value, obj_to_call, args)
7227  elseif (present(kwargs)) then
7228  ierror = call_py(return_value, obj_to_call, kwargs=kwargs)
7229  else
7230  ierror = call_py(return_value, obj_to_call)
7231  endif
7232 
7233  call return_value%destroy
7234 end function

7238 
7239 function ndarray_create_nocopy_int32_1d(res, array) result(ierror)
7240  !> The resulting ndarray (in Fortran storage order).
7241  type(ndarray), intent(out) :: res
7242  !> The Fortran array to wrap as ndarray. NO copy is made. Changes to the ndarray affect the Fortran array and
7243  !> vice versa. MUST be a contiguous array (this is not checked).
7244  ! Note: can not use the F2008 CONTIGUOUS attribute here, because a
7245  ! temporary copy of array could be created with limited lifetime.
7246  integer(kind=int32), dimension(:), target, intent(in) :: array
7247  !> Error code, 0 on success
7248  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
7249 
7250  integer, parameter :: NDIM = 1
7251  integer(kind=PY_SSIZE_T_KIND), parameter :: ITEMSIZE = 4_PY_SSIZE_T_KIND
7252 
7253 #ifndef PYTHON2
7254  ierror = ndarray_create_nocopy_helper(res, c_loc(array), shape(array, kind=PY_SSIZE_T_KIND), NDIM, ITEMSIZE, "i" // C_NULL_CHAR)
7255 #else
7256  ierror = ndarray_create_nocopy_helper_py2(res, c_loc(array), shape(array, kind=PY_SSIZE_T_KIND), NDIM, ITEMSIZE, "int32")
7257 #endif
7258 
7259 end function
7260 
7261 function ndarray_create_int32_1d(res, array) result(ierror)
7262  !> The resulting ndarray (in Fortran storage order).
7263  type(ndarray), intent(out) :: res
7264  !> Create a new ndarray with a copy of the data given in 'array'
7265  integer(kind=int32), dimension(:), intent(in) :: array
7266  !> Error code, 0 on success
7267  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
7268 
7269  integer(kind=int32), dimension(:), pointer :: ptr
7270 
7271  ierror = ndarray_create_empty(res, shape(array, kind=PY_SSIZE_T_KIND), "int32")
7272  if (ierror /= 0_C_INT) return
7273  ierror = res%get_data(ptr)
7274  if (ierror /= 0_C_INT) then
7275  call res%destroy
7276  res%py_object = C_NULL_PTR
7277  return
7278  endif
7279  ptr = array
7280 end function
7281 
7282 !> Get pointer to data of numpy array
7283 !>
7284 !> Raises BufferError, if array is not contiguous (does not have the required Fortran or C storage order)
7285 !> Raises TypeError, if Fortran pointer datatype is not compatible with numpy datatype.
7286 function get_data_int32_1d(self, ptr, order) result(ierror)
7287  class(ndarray), intent(in) :: self
7288  !> Pointer to the numerical data of the Fortran array.
7289  integer(kind=int32), dimension(:), pointer, intent(out) :: ptr
7290  !> Only retrieve data, when ndarray has certain order.
7291  !>
7292  !> If 'F' (default), only retrieve the data when the ndarray has Fortran storage order.
7293  !> If 'C', only retrieve the data when the ndarray has C storage order.
7294  !> ATTENTION: The data, the pointer points to, then will be the transpose of the array.
7295  !> If 'A' accept Fortran or C order. If C, the data will be transposed.
7296  character(kind=C_CHAR), optional, intent(in) :: order
7297  !> Error code, 0 on success
7298  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
7299 
7300  character(kind=C_CHAR) :: the_order
7301  type(c_ptr) :: raw_ptr
7302  integer, parameter :: NDIM = 1
7303  integer(kind=PY_SSIZE_T_KIND), dimension(NDIM) :: shape_info
7304 
7305 .not. if ( present(order)) then
7306  the_order = 'F'
7307  else
7308  the_order = order
7309  endif
7310 
7311  nullify(ptr)
7312  ierror = get_data_helper(self, raw_ptr, shape_info, NDIM, "i" // C_NULL_CHAR, the_order)
7313 
7314  if (ierror == 0_C_INT) then
7315  call c_f_pointer(raw_ptr, ptr, shape=shape_info)
7316 .not. if ( associated(ptr)) then
7317  ierror = EXCEPTION_ERROR
7318  call raise_exception(RuntimeError, "forpy: could not determine shape of ndarray")
7319  endif
7320  endif
7321 end function

7323 function ndarray_create_nocopy_int64_1d(res, array) result(ierror)

7325  type(ndarray), intent(out) :: res
7326  !> The Fortran array to wrap as ndarray. NO copy is made. Changes to the ndarray affect the Fortran array and

7337 #ifndef PYTHON2

7339 #else
7340  ierror = ndarray_create_nocopy_helper_py2(res, c_loc(array), shape(array, kind=PY_SSIZE_T_KIND), NDIM, ITEMSIZE, "int64")
7341 #endif

7366 !> Get pointer to data of numpy array
7367 !>
7368 !> Raises BufferError, if array is not contiguous (does not have the required Fortran or C storage order)
7369 !> Raises TypeError, if Fortran pointer datatype is not compatible with numpy datatype.
7370 function get_data_int64_1d(self, ptr, order) result(ierror)
7371  class(ndarray), intent(in) :: self
7372  !> Pointer to the numerical data of the Fortran array.
7373  integer(kind=int64), dimension(:), pointer, intent(out) :: ptr
7374  !> Only retrieve data, when ndarray has certain order.
7375  !>
7376  !> If 'F' (default), only retrieve the data when the ndarray has Fortran storage order.
7377  !> If 'C', only retrieve the data when the ndarray has C storage order.
7378  !> ATTENTION: The data, the pointer points to, then will be the transpose of the array.
7379  !> If 'A' accept Fortran or C order. If C, the data will be transposed.
7380  character(kind=C_CHAR), optional, intent(in) :: order
7381  !> Error code, 0 on success
7382  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
7383 
7384  character(kind=C_CHAR) :: the_order
7385  type(c_ptr) :: raw_ptr
7386  integer, parameter :: NDIM = 1
7387  integer(kind=PY_SSIZE_T_KIND), dimension(NDIM) :: shape_info
7388 
7389 .not. if ( present(order)) then
7390  the_order = 'F'
7391  else
7392  the_order = order
7393  endif
7394 
7395  nullify(ptr)
7396  ierror = get_data_helper(self, raw_ptr, shape_info, NDIM, "l" // C_NULL_CHAR, the_order)
7397 
7398  if (ierror == 0_C_INT) then
7399  call c_f_pointer(raw_ptr, ptr, shape=shape_info)
7400 .not. if ( associated(ptr)) then
7401  ierror = EXCEPTION_ERROR
7402  call raise_exception(RuntimeError, "forpy: could not determine shape of ndarray")
7403  endif
7404  endif
7405 end function

7804  character(kind=C_CHAR) :: the_order
7805  type(c_ptr) :: raw_ptr
7806  integer, parameter :: NDIM = 2
7807  integer(kind=PY_SSIZE_T_KIND), dimension(NDIM) :: shape_info
7808 
7809 .not. if ( present(order)) then
7810  the_order = 'F'
7811  else
7812  the_order = order
7813  endif
7814 
7815  nullify(ptr)
7816  ierror = get_data_helper(self, raw_ptr, shape_info, NDIM, "i" // C_NULL_CHAR, the_order)
7817 
7818  if (ierror == 0_C_INT) then
7819  call c_f_pointer(raw_ptr, ptr, shape=shape_info)
7820 .not. if ( associated(ptr)) then
7821  ierror = EXCEPTION_ERROR
7822  call raise_exception(RuntimeError, "forpy: could not determine shape of ndarray")
7823  endif
7824  endif
7825 end function

7827 function ndarray_create_nocopy_int64_2d(res, array) result(ierror)
7828  !> The resulting ndarray (in Fortran storage order).
7829  type(ndarray), intent(out) :: res
7830  !> The Fortran array to wrap as ndarray. NO copy is made. Changes to the ndarray affect the Fortran array and
7831  !> vice versa. MUST be a contiguous array (this is not checked).
7832  ! Note: can not use the F2008 CONTIGUOUS attribute here, because a
7833  ! temporary copy of array could be created with limited lifetime.
7834  integer(kind=int64), dimension(:,:), target, intent(in) :: array
7835  !> Error code, 0 on success
7836  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
7837 
7838  integer, parameter :: NDIM = 2
7839  integer(kind=PY_SSIZE_T_KIND), parameter :: ITEMSIZE = 8_PY_SSIZE_T_KIND
7840 
7841 #ifndef PYTHON2
7842  ierror = ndarray_create_nocopy_helper(res, c_loc(array), shape(array, kind=PY_SSIZE_T_KIND), NDIM, ITEMSIZE, "l" // C_NULL_CHAR)
7843 #else
7844  ierror = ndarray_create_nocopy_helper_py2(res, c_loc(array), shape(array, kind=PY_SSIZE_T_KIND), NDIM, ITEMSIZE, "int64")
7845 #endif
7846 
7847 end function

7856 
7857  integer(kind=int64), dimension(:,:), pointer :: ptr

7874 function get_data_int64_2d(self, ptr, order) result(ierror)

7876  !> Pointer to the numerical data of the Fortran array.
7877  integer(kind=int64), dimension(:,:), pointer, intent(out) :: ptr
7878  !> Only retrieve data, when ndarray has certain order.
7879  !>
7880  !> If 'F' (default), only retrieve the data when the ndarray has Fortran storage order.
7881  !> If 'C', only retrieve the data when the ndarray has C storage order.
7882  !> ATTENTION: The data, the pointer points to, then will be the transpose of the array.
7883  !> If 'A' accept Fortran or C order. If C, the data will be transposed.
7884  character(kind=C_CHAR), optional, intent(in) :: order
7885  !> Error code, 0 on success
7886  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
7887 
7888  character(kind=C_CHAR) :: the_order
7889  type(c_ptr) :: raw_ptr
7890  integer, parameter :: NDIM = 2
7891  integer(kind=PY_SSIZE_T_KIND), dimension(NDIM) :: shape_info
7892 
7893 .not. if ( present(order)) then
7894  the_order = 'F'
7895  else
7896  the_order = order
7897  endif
7898 
7899  nullify(ptr)
7900  ierror = get_data_helper(self, raw_ptr, shape_info, NDIM, "l" // C_NULL_CHAR, the_order)
7901 
7902  if (ierror == 0_C_INT) then
7903  call c_f_pointer(raw_ptr, ptr, shape=shape_info)
7904 .not. if ( associated(ptr)) then
7905  ierror = EXCEPTION_ERROR
7906  call raise_exception(RuntimeError, "forpy: could not determine shape of ndarray")
7907  endif
7908  endif
7909 end function

8298  !> Only retrieve data, when ndarray has certain order.
8299  !>
8300  !> If 'F' (default), only retrieve the data when the ndarray has Fortran storage order.
8301  !> If 'C', only retrieve the data when the ndarray has C storage order.
8302  !> ATTENTION: The data, the pointer points to, then will be the transpose of the array.
8303  !> If 'A' accept Fortran or C order. If C, the data will be transposed.
8304  character(kind=C_CHAR), optional, intent(in) :: order
8305  !> Error code, 0 on success
8306  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
8307 
8308  character(kind=C_CHAR) :: the_order
8309  type(c_ptr) :: raw_ptr
8310  integer, parameter :: NDIM = 3
8311  integer(kind=PY_SSIZE_T_KIND), dimension(NDIM) :: shape_info
8312 
8313 .not. if ( present(order)) then
8314  the_order = 'F'
8315  else
8316  the_order = order
8317  endif
8318 
8319  nullify(ptr)
8320  ierror = get_data_helper(self, raw_ptr, shape_info, NDIM, "i" // C_NULL_CHAR, the_order)
8321 
8322  if (ierror == 0_C_INT) then
8323  call c_f_pointer(raw_ptr, ptr, shape=shape_info)
8324 .not. if ( associated(ptr)) then
8325  ierror = EXCEPTION_ERROR
8326  call raise_exception(RuntimeError, "forpy: could not determine shape of ndarray")
8327  endif
8328  endif
8329 end function

8331 function ndarray_create_nocopy_int64_3d(res, array) result(ierror)
8332  !> The resulting ndarray (in Fortran storage order).
8333  type(ndarray), intent(out) :: res
8334  !> The Fortran array to wrap as ndarray. NO copy is made. Changes to the ndarray affect the Fortran array and
8335  !> vice versa. MUST be a contiguous array (this is not checked).
8336  ! Note: can not use the F2008 CONTIGUOUS attribute here, because a
8337  ! temporary copy of array could be created with limited lifetime.
8338  integer(kind=int64), dimension(:,:,:), target, intent(in) :: array
8339  !> Error code, 0 on success
8340  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
8341 
8342  integer, parameter :: NDIM = 3
8343  integer(kind=PY_SSIZE_T_KIND), parameter :: ITEMSIZE = 8_PY_SSIZE_T_KIND
8344 
8345 #ifndef PYTHON2
8346  ierror = ndarray_create_nocopy_helper(res, c_loc(array), shape(array, kind=PY_SSIZE_T_KIND), NDIM, ITEMSIZE, "l" // C_NULL_CHAR)
8347 #else
8348  ierror = ndarray_create_nocopy_helper_py2(res, c_loc(array), shape(array, kind=PY_SSIZE_T_KIND), NDIM, ITEMSIZE, "int64")
8349 #endif
8350 
8351 end function

8785  ierror = res%get_data(ptr)
8786  if (ierror /= 0_C_INT) then
8787  call res%destroy
8788  res%py_object = C_NULL_PTR
8789  return
8790  endif
8791  ptr = array
8792 end function
8793 
8794 !> Get pointer to data of numpy array
8795 !>
8796 !> Raises BufferError, if array is not contiguous (does not have the required Fortran or C storage order)
8797 !> Raises TypeError, if Fortran pointer datatype is not compatible with numpy datatype.
8798 function get_data_int32_4d(self, ptr, order) result(ierror)
8799  class(ndarray), intent(in) :: self
8800  !> Pointer to the numerical data of the Fortran array.
8801  integer(kind=int32), dimension(:,:,:,:), pointer, intent(out) :: ptr
8802  !> Only retrieve data, when ndarray has certain order.
8803  !>
8804  !> If 'F' (default), only retrieve the data when the ndarray has Fortran storage order.
8805  !> If 'C', only retrieve the data when the ndarray has C storage order.
8806  !> ATTENTION: The data, the pointer points to, then will be the transpose of the array.
8807  !> If 'A' accept Fortran or C order. If C, the data will be transposed.
8808  character(kind=C_CHAR), optional, intent(in) :: order
8809  !> Error code, 0 on success
8810  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
8811 
8812  character(kind=C_CHAR) :: the_order
8813  type(c_ptr) :: raw_ptr
8814  integer, parameter :: NDIM = 4
8815  integer(kind=PY_SSIZE_T_KIND), dimension(NDIM) :: shape_info
8816 
8817 .not. if ( present(order)) then
8818  the_order = 'F'
8819  else
8820  the_order = order
8821  endif
8822 
8823  nullify(ptr)
8824  ierror = get_data_helper(self, raw_ptr, shape_info, NDIM, "i" // C_NULL_CHAR, the_order)
8825 
8826  if (ierror == 0_C_INT) then
8827  call c_f_pointer(raw_ptr, ptr, shape=shape_info)
8828 .not. if ( associated(ptr)) then
8829  ierror = EXCEPTION_ERROR
8830  call raise_exception(RuntimeError, "forpy: could not determine shape of ndarray")
8831  endif
8832  endif
8833 end function

8835 function ndarray_create_nocopy_int64_4d(res, array) result(ierror)
8836  !> The resulting ndarray (in Fortran storage order).
8837  type(ndarray), intent(out) :: res
8838  !> The Fortran array to wrap as ndarray. NO copy is made. Changes to the ndarray affect the Fortran array and
8839  !> vice versa. MUST be a contiguous array (this is not checked).
8840  ! Note: can not use the F2008 CONTIGUOUS attribute here, because a
8841  ! temporary copy of array could be created with limited lifetime.
8842  integer(kind=int64), dimension(:,:,:,:), target, intent(in) :: array
8843  !> Error code, 0 on success
8844  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
8845 
8846  integer, parameter :: NDIM = 4
8847  integer(kind=PY_SSIZE_T_KIND), parameter :: ITEMSIZE = 8_PY_SSIZE_T_KIND
8848 
8849 #ifndef PYTHON2
8850  ierror = ndarray_create_nocopy_helper(res, c_loc(array), shape(array, kind=PY_SSIZE_T_KIND), NDIM, ITEMSIZE, "l" // C_NULL_CHAR)
8851 #else
8852  ierror = ndarray_create_nocopy_helper_py2(res, c_loc(array), shape(array, kind=PY_SSIZE_T_KIND), NDIM, ITEMSIZE, "int64")
8853 #endif
8854 
8855 end function

9257 function ndarray_create_nocopy_helper(res, array_c_loc, array_shape, ndim, itemsize, format_c_string) result(ierror)
9258  type(ndarray), intent(inout) :: res
9259  type(c_ptr), intent(in) :: array_c_loc
9260  integer, intent(in) :: ndim
9261  integer(kind=PY_SSIZE_T_KIND), target, dimension(ndim), intent(in) :: array_shape
9262  integer(kind=PY_SSIZE_T_KIND) :: itemsize
9263  character(kind=C_CHAR, len=*), target, intent(in) :: format_c_string
9264  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
9265 
9266  type(Py_buffer) :: buffer
9267  integer(kind=PY_SSIZE_T_KIND), target, dimension(ndim) :: strides
9268  integer(kind=PY_SSIZE_T_KIND) :: length
9269  type(c_ptr) :: mem_view
9270  type(c_ptr) :: args
9271  integer :: ii
9272 
9273  !TODO: check if numpy was successfully imported
9274 
9275  ierror = 0_C_INT
9276  res%py_object = C_NULL_PTR
9277 
9278  length = 1
9279  do ii = 1, ndim
9280  length = length * array_shape(ii)
9281  enddo
9282 
9283  ! calculate the strides assuming Fortran-order
9284  call PyBuffer_FillContiguousStrides(int(ndim, kind=C_INT), c_loc(array_shape), c_loc(strides), itemsize, 'F')
9285 
9286  buffer%buf = array_c_loc
9287  buffer%obj = C_NULL_PTR
9288  buffer%len = length * ITEMSIZE
9289  buffer%itemsize = itemsize
9290  buffer%readonly = 0_C_INT
9291  buffer%ndim = int(ndim, C_INT)
9292  buffer%format = c_loc(format_c_string)
9293  buffer%shape = c_loc(array_shape)
9294  buffer%strides = c_loc(strides)
9295  buffer%suboffsets = C_NULL_PTR
9296 #ifdef PYTHON2
9297  buffer%smalltable = 0_PY_SSIZE_T_KIND
9298 #endif
9299  buffer%internal = C_NULL_PTR
9300 
9301  mem_view = PyMemoryView_FromBuffer(buffer)
9302 .not. if ( c_associated(mem_view)) then
9303  ierror = -1_C_INT
9304  return
9305  endif
9306 
9307  args = PyTuple_New(1_PY_SSIZE_T_KIND)
9308  if (c_associated(args)) then
9309  ierror = PyTuple_SetItem(args, 0_PY_SSIZE_T_KIND, mem_view) ! steals reference to mem_view even if it fails
9310 
9311  if (ierror /= 0_C_INT) then
9312  call Py_Decref(args)
9313  return
9314  endif
9315 
9316  res%py_object = PyObject_Call(global_numpy_asarray_method, args, C_NULL_PTR)
9317  call Py_Decref(args)
9318 
9319 .not. if ( c_associated(res%py_object)) then
9320  ierror = -1_C_INT
9321  endif
9322 
9323 .not. else ! c_associated(args)
9324  call Py_Decref(mem_view)
9325  ierror = -1_C_INT
9326  endif
9327 
9328 end function
9329 #endif
9330 
9331 #ifdef PYTHON2
9332 ! Python 2 array wrapper creation using old-style, py2-only buffer object + np.frombuffer.
9333 ! In principle with Py 2.7 it would be possible to use the same code as
9334 ! in the Py 3 case, but the memoryview + np.asarray
9335 ! approach is somewhat buggy in Py 2 and one reference is lost
9336 function ndarray_create_nocopy_helper_py2(res, array_c_loc, array_shape, ndim, itemsize, dtype) result(ierror)
9337  type(ndarray), intent(inout) :: res
9338  type(c_ptr), intent(in) :: array_c_loc
9339  integer, intent(in) :: ndim
9340  integer(kind=PY_SSIZE_T_KIND), target, dimension(ndim), intent(in) :: array_shape
9341  integer(kind=PY_SSIZE_T_KIND) :: itemsize
9342  character(kind=C_CHAR, len=*), target, intent(in) :: dtype
9343  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
9344 
9345  integer(kind=PY_SSIZE_T_KIND) :: length
9346  type(c_ptr) :: buffer_obj
9347  type(module_py) :: numpy
9348  type(tuple) :: args
9349  type(object) :: retval
9350  type(object) :: buffer
9351  type(ndarray) :: reshaped_array
9352  integer :: ii
9353 
9354  ierror = -1_C_INT
9355  res%py_object = C_NULL_PTR
9356 
9357  length = 1
9358  do ii = 1, ndim
9359  length = length * array_shape(ii)
9360  enddo
9361 
9362  buffer_obj = PyBuffer_FromReadWriteMemory(array_c_loc, length*itemsize)
9363 .not. if ( c_associated(buffer_obj)) then
9364  return
9365  endif
9366 
9367  buffer%py_object = buffer_obj
9368 
9369  ierror = tuple_create(args, 2_PY_SSIZE_T_KIND)
9370  if (ierror /= 0_C_INT) then
9371  call buffer%destroy
9372  return
9373  endif
9374 
9375  ierror = args%setitem(0_PY_SSIZE_T_KIND, buffer)
9376  if (ierror /= 0_C_INT) then
9377  call args%destroy
9378  call buffer%destroy
9379  return
9380  endif
9381 
9382  ierror = args%setitem(1_PY_SSIZE_T_KIND, dtype)
9383  if (ierror /= 0_C_INT) then
9384  call args%destroy
9385  call buffer%destroy
9386  return
9387  endif
9388 
9389  numpy%py_object = global_numpy_mod
9390  ierror = call_py(retval, numpy, "frombuffer", args)
9391  call args%destroy
9392  call buffer%destroy
9393 
9394  if (ierror == 0_C_INT) then
9395  res%py_object = retval%py_object
9396  else
9397  call retval%destroy
9398  return
9399  endif
9400 
9401  if (ndim > 1) then
9402  ierror = ndarray_reshape_helper(reshaped_array, res, array_shape, 'F')
9403  call res%destroy
9404 
9405  if (ierror == 0_C_INT) then
9406  res%py_object = reshaped_array%py_object
9407  else
9408  res%py_object = C_NULL_PTR
9409  endif
9410  endif
9411 end function
9412 
9413 function ndarray_reshape_helper(reshaped_array, array, new_shape, order) result(ierror)
9414  type(ndarray), intent(out) :: reshaped_array
9415  class(ndarray), intent(in) :: array
9416  integer(kind=PY_SSIZE_T_KIND), dimension(:), intent(in) :: new_shape
9417  character(kind=C_CHAR), intent(in) :: order
9418  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
9419 
9420  type(tuple) :: args
9421  type(dict) :: kwargs
9422  type(tuple) :: new_shape_tuple
9423  type(object) :: retval
9424 
9425  reshaped_array%py_object = C_NULL_PTR
9426 
9427  ierror = tuple_from_array(new_shape_tuple, new_shape)
9428  if (ierror /= 0_C_INT) then
9429  return
9430  endif
9431 
9432  ierror = tuple_create(args, 1_PY_SSIZE_T_KIND)
9433  if (ierror /= 0_C_INT) then
9434  call new_shape_tuple%destroy
9435  return
9436  endif
9437 
9438  ierror = args%setitem(0_PY_SSIZE_T_KIND, new_shape_tuple)
9439  if (ierror /= 0_C_INT) then
9440  call args%destroy
9441  call new_shape_tuple%destroy
9442  return
9443  endif
9444 
9445  ierror = dict_create(kwargs)
9446  if (ierror /= 0_C_INT) then
9447  call args%destroy
9448  call new_shape_tuple%destroy
9449  return
9450  endif
9451

9453  if (ierror /= 0_C_INT) then
9454  call kwargs%destroy
9455  call args%destroy
9456  call new_shape_tuple%destroy
9457  return
9458  endif
9459 
9460  ierror = call_py(retval, array, "reshape", args, kwargs)
9461  if (ierror == 0_C_INT) then
9462  ierror = cast(reshaped_array, retval)
9463  call retval%destroy
9464  endif
9465 
9466  call kwargs%destroy
9467  call args%destroy
9468  call new_shape_tuple%destroy
9469 end function

9471 
9472 !> Get pointer to data of numpy array
9473 function get_data_helper(self, raw_ptr, shape_info, ndim, format_c_string, order) result(ierror)
9474  class(ndarray), intent(in) :: self
9475  type(c_ptr), intent(out) :: raw_ptr
9476  integer, intent(in) :: ndim
9477  integer(kind=PY_SSIZE_T_KIND), dimension(ndim), intent(out) :: shape_info
9478  character(kind=C_CHAR, len=*), target, intent(in) :: format_c_string
9479  character(kind=C_CHAR), intent(in) :: order
9480 
9481  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror, flag
9482  type(Py_buffer) :: buffer
9483  integer(kind=PY_SSIZE_T_KIND), dimension(:), pointer :: shape_ptr
9484  integer :: shape_info_shape(1)
9485  character(kind=C_CHAR) :: detected_order
9486  character(kind=C_CHAR,len=60) :: error_message
9487 
9488  ! order can have values 'C', 'F' or 'A'
9489  if (index('CFA', order) == 0) then
9490  ierror = EXCEPTION_ERROR
9491  call raise_exception(ValueError, "ndarray%get_data: order parameter must be 'F', 'C' or 'A'")
9492  return
9493  endif
9494 
9495  shape_info_shape(1) = ndim
9496 
9497  ! raises BufferError exception if array is not contiguous, Python 2: ValueError
9498  ierror = PyObject_GetBuffer(self%py_object, buffer, 156_C_INT) !flags (PyBUF_FORMAT | PyBUF_ANY_CONTIGUOUS) - we need the format info and PyBUF_FORMAT alone gives error
9499 
9500  if (ierror /= 0) then
9501 .or. if (exception_matches(BufferError) exception_matches(ValueError)) then ! make error message more informative
9502  call err_clear
9503  call raise_exception(BufferError, "forpy: ndarray with non-contiguous data. fortran or c-order needed: try to copy array")
9504  endif
9505  return
9506  endif
9507 
9508  detected_order = 'N'
9509  flag = PyBuffer_IsContiguous(buffer, 'F')
9510  if (flag == 1_C_INT) then
9511  detected_order = 'F'
9512  else
9513  flag = PyBuffer_IsContiguous(buffer, 'C')
9514  if (flag == 1_C_INT) then
9515  detected_order = 'C'
9516  endif
9517  endif
9518 
9519 .or..and..and. if ((detected_order == 'N') (ndim > 1 order /= 'A' order /= detected_order)) then
9520  ierror = EXCEPTION_ERROR
9521  if (order=='F') then
9522  error_message = "forpy: expected fortran-ordered array"
9523  elseif (order=='C') then
9524  error_message = "forpy: expected c-ordered array"
9525  else
9526  error_message = "forpy: expected contiguous array"
9527  endif
9528  call PyBuffer_Release(buffer)
9529  call raise_exception(BufferError, error_message)
9530  return
9531  endif
9532 
9533  if (buffer%ndim /= ndim) then
9534  ierror = EXCEPTION_ERROR
9535  write(error_message,fmt="('forpy: expected array of rank ',i1,', got array of rank ',i1)") ndim, buffer%ndim
9536  call PyBuffer_Release(buffer)
9537  call raise_exception(TypeError, error_message)
9538  return
9539  endif
9540 
9541  !get shape info
9542  call c_f_pointer(buffer%shape, shape_ptr, shape=SHAPE_INFO_SHAPE)
9543 
9544  !check if correct format
9545  if (associated(shape_ptr)) then
9546  if (get_data_helper_check_dtype(buffer%format, format_c_string) /= 0) then
9547  ierror = EXCEPTION_ERROR
9548  call PyBuffer_Release(buffer)
9549  call raise_exception(TypeError, "forpy: ndarray%get_data - datatype of data pointer is incompatible with ndarray")
9550  return
9551  endif
9552  else
9553  ierror = EXCEPTION_ERROR
9554  call PyBuffer_Release(buffer)
9555  call raise_exception(RuntimeError, "forpy: could not determine shape of ndarray")
9556  return
9557  endif
9558 
9559  raw_ptr = buffer%buf
9560 
9561  call get_shape_info_helper(shape_info, shape_ptr, detected_order)
9562  call PyBuffer_Release(buffer)
9563 
9564 end function
9565 
9566 ! returns 0 if dtype matches fortran type, non-zero if not
9567 function get_data_helper_check_dtype(buffer_format, format_c_string) result(flag)
9568  type(c_ptr), intent(in) :: buffer_format
9569  character(kind=C_CHAR, len=*), target, intent(in) :: format_c_string
9570 
9571  character(kind=C_CHAR, len=2), target :: format_code
9572  integer(kind=C_INT) :: flag
9573 
9574  flag = 1_C_INT
9575 
9576  ! the Python buffer format codes corresponding to int32 and int64 are systems dependent...
9577 
9578  if (format_c_string == "i" // C_NULL_CHAR) then ! buffer type compatible with int32 requested
9579  if (int32 == C_INT) then
9580  format_code = "i" // C_NULL_CHAR
9581  flag = strcmp(buffer_format, c_loc(format_code))
9582  endif
9583  if (flag /= 0) then
9584  if (int32 == C_LONG) then
9585  format_code = "l" // C_NULL_CHAR
9586  flag = strcmp(buffer_format, c_loc(format_code))
9587  endif
9588  endif
9589  return
9590  endif
9591 
9592  if (format_c_string == "l" // C_NULL_CHAR) then ! buffer type compatible with int64 requested
9593  if (int64 == C_LONG) then
9594  format_code = "l" // C_NULL_CHAR
9595  flag = strcmp(buffer_format, c_loc(format_code))
9596  endif
9597  if (flag /= 0) then
9598  if (int64 == C_LONG_LONG) then
9599  format_code = "q" // C_NULL_CHAR
9600  flag = strcmp(buffer_format, c_loc(format_code))
9601  endif
9602  endif
9603  if (flag /= 0) then
9604  if (int64 == C_INT) then
9605  format_code = "i" // C_NULL_CHAR
9606  flag = strcmp(buffer_format, c_loc(format_code))
9607  endif
9608  endif
9609  return
9610  endif
9611 
9612  ! this handles all the non-integer cases
9613  flag = strcmp(buffer_format, c_loc(format_c_string))
9614 end function
9615 
9616 subroutine get_shape_info_helper(shape_info, shape_ptr, order)
9617  integer(kind=PY_SSIZE_T_KIND), dimension(:), intent(out) :: shape_info
9618  integer(kind=PY_SSIZE_T_KIND), dimension(:), intent(in) :: shape_ptr
9619  character(kind=C_CHAR), intent(in) :: order
9620 
9621  integer ii, length
9622 
9623  if (order == 'F') then
9624  shape_info = shape_ptr
9625  elseif (order == 'C') then ! C-order: reverse shape information ("transpose")
9626  length = size(shape_info)
9627  do ii = 1, length
9628  shape_info(ii) = shape_ptr(length-ii+1)
9629  enddo
9630  endif
9631 end subroutine

9649 !>
9650 !> order (optional) can be 'F', 'C', 'A' or 'K'
9651 !> (default is 'F' - in numpy it is 'C')
9652 function ndarray_copy(self, array_copy, order) result(ierror)
9653  class(ndarray), intent(in) :: self
9654  type(ndarray), intent(out) :: array_copy
9655  character(kind=C_CHAR), intent(in), optional :: order

9657

9659  type(object) :: retval
9660  type(tuple) :: args

9662 .not. if ( present(order)) then

9666  endif

9686 !> Checks if data of ndarray has a specific storage-order.
9687 !>
9688 !> order can be 'F' (Fortran-order), 'C' (C-order), 'A' (Fortran- or C-order)
9689 function ndarray_is_ordered(self, order) result(is_ordered)
9690  class(ndarray), intent(in) :: self
9691  character(kind=C_CHAR), intent(in) :: order
9692  logical :: is_ordered
9693 
9694  type(object) :: retval, flags
9695  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
9696  logical :: c_ordered, fortran_ordered, check_c, check_f
9697 
9698  is_ordered = .false.
9699  c_ordered = .false.
9700  fortran_ordered = .false.
9701 
9702  if (have_exception()) return
9703 
9704  ierror = self%getattribute(flags, "flags")
9705  if (ierror /= 0_C_INT) then
9706  call err_clear
9707  return
9708  endif
9709 
9710 .or. check_f = (order == 'F') (order == 'A')
9711 
9712  if (check_f) then
9713  ierror = flags%getattribute(retval, "f_contiguous")
9714  if (ierror /= 0_C_INT) then
9715  call flags%destroy
9716  call err_clear
9717  return
9718  endif
9719  ierror = cast(fortran_ordered, retval)
9720  call retval%destroy
9721  if (ierror /= 0_C_INT) then
9722  call flags%destroy
9723  call err_clear
9724  return
9725  endif
9726  endif
9727 
9728 .or..and..not. check_c = (order == 'C') (order == 'A' fortran_ordered)
9729 
9730  if (check_c) then
9731  ierror = flags%getattribute(retval, "c_contiguous")
9732  if (ierror /= 0_C_INT) then
9733  call flags%destroy
9734  call err_clear
9735  return
9736  endif
9737  ierror = cast(c_ordered, retval)
9738  call retval%destroy
9739  if (ierror /= 0_C_INT) then
9740  call flags%destroy
9741  call err_clear
9742  return
9743  endif
9744  endif
9745 
9746  call flags%destroy
9747 .or. is_ordered = fortran_ordered c_ordered
9748 
9749 end function

9817 function ndarray_create_empty_aint32(array, a_shape, dtype, order) result(ierror)

9874 function ndarray_create_empty_int32(array, length, dtype, order) result(ierror)
9875  !> The resulting one dimensional ndarray.
9876  type(ndarray), intent(out) :: array

9879  !> numpy.dtype of ndarray (default: 'float')

9882  character(kind=C_CHAR), intent(in), optional :: order
9883  !> Error code, 0 on success
9884  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
9885 
9886  integer(kind=int32) :: a_shape(1)
9887  a_shape(1) = length
9888 
9889  if (present(dtype)) then
9890  if (present(order)) then
9891  ierror = ndarray_create_special_impl_int32(array, "empty", a_shape, dtype, order)
9892  else
9893  ! Fortran order as default, in contrast to numpy
9894  ierror = ndarray_create_special_impl_int32(array, "empty", a_shape, dtype, "f")
9895  endif
9896  else
9897  if (present(order)) then
9898  ierror = ndarray_create_special_impl_int32(array, "empty", a_shape, "", order)
9899  else
9900  ierror = ndarray_create_special_impl_int32(array, "empty", a_shape, "", "f")
9901  endif
9902  endif
9903 end function

10175 function ndarray_create_special_impl_int32(array, creator_function, a_shape, dtype, order) result(ierror)
10176  type(ndarray), intent(out) :: array
10177  character(kind=C_CHAR, len=*), intent(in) :: creator_function
10178  integer(kind=int32), dimension(:), intent(in) :: a_shape
10179  character(kind=C_CHAR, len=*), intent(in) :: dtype
10180  character(kind=C_CHAR), intent(in) :: order
10181  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
10182 
10183  type(dict) :: kwargs
10184 
10185  ierror = dict_create(kwargs)
10186  if (ierror /= 0_C_INT) return
10187 
10188  if (len(dtype) > 0) then
10189  ierror = kwargs%setitem("dtype", dtype)
10190  if (ierror /= 0_C_INT) then
10191  call kwargs%destroy
10192  return
10193  endif
10194  endif
10195 
10196  ierror = kwargs%setitem("order", order)
10197 
10198  if (ierror == 0_C_INT) then
10199  ierror = ndarray_create_special_helper_int32(array, creator_function, a_shape, kwargs)
10200  endif
10201 
10202  call kwargs%destroy
10203 end function
10204 
10205 function ndarray_create_special_getargs_int32(args, a_shape) result(ierror)
10206  type(tuple), intent(out) :: args
10207  integer(kind=int32), dimension(:), intent(in) :: a_shape
10208  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
10209 
10210  type(tuple) :: shape_tuple
10211 
10212  ierror = tuple_from_array_int32(shape_tuple, a_shape)
10213  if (ierror /= 0_C_INT) return
10214 
10215  ierror = tuple_create(args, 1_PY_SSIZE_T_KIND)
10216  if (ierror /= 0_C_INT) then
10217  call shape_tuple%destroy
10218  return
10219  endif
10220 
10221  ierror = args%setitem(0_PY_SSIZE_T_KIND, shape_tuple)
10222  call shape_tuple%destroy
10223 end function
10224 
10225 function ndarray_create_special_helper_int32(array, creator_function, a_shape, kwargs) result(ierror)
10226  type(ndarray), intent(out) :: array
10227  character(kind=C_CHAR, len=*), intent(in) :: creator_function
10228  integer(kind=int32), dimension(:), intent(in) :: a_shape
10229  type(dict), intent(in) :: kwargs
10230  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
10231 
10232  type(tuple) :: args
10233  type(object) :: retval
10234  type(module_py) :: numpy_mod
10235 
10236  ierror = ndarray_create_special_getargs_int32(args, a_shape)
10237  if (ierror /= 0_C_INT) return
10238 
10239  numpy_mod%py_object = global_numpy_mod
10240  ierror = call_py(retval, numpy_mod, creator_function, args, kwargs)
10241 
10242  if (ierror == 0_C_INT) then
10243  ierror = cast(array, retval)
10244  call retval%destroy
10245  endif
10246 
10247  call args%destroy
10248 
10249 end function
10250 
10251 !> Helper function: create tuple from integer array
10252 function tuple_from_array_int32(tu, arr) result(ierror)
10253  type(tuple), intent(out) :: tu
10254  integer(kind=int32), dimension(:), intent(in) :: arr
10255  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
10256 
10257  integer(kind=PY_SSIZE_T_KIND) :: ii, ndim
10258  ndim = size(arr, kind=PY_SSIZE_T_KIND)
10259 
10260  ierror = tuple_create(tu, ndim)
10261  if (ierror /= 0_C_INT) return
10262 
10263  do ii = 1, ndim
10264  ierror = tu%setitem(ii-1, arr(ii))
10265  if (ierror /= 0_C_INT) then
10266  call tu%destroy
10267  return
10268  endif
10269  enddo
10270 end function

10370 !------------------ Routines for wrapping values into Python objects ("boxing") ----------------------
10371 #ifndef PYTHON2
10372 function box_value_int32_as_long(obj, the_value) result(ierror)
10373  type(c_ptr), intent(out) :: obj
10374  integer(kind=int32), intent(in) :: the_value
10375  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
10376 
10377  integer(kind=C_LONG_LONG) :: tmp
10378  ierror = 0_C_INT
10379 
10380  tmp = int(the_value, C_LONG_LONG)
10381 
10382  obj = PyLong_FromLongLong(tmp)
10383 
10384 .not. if ( c_associated(obj)) then
10385  ierror = EXCEPTION_ERROR
10386  endif
10387 
10388 end function
10389 #endif
10390 
10391 function box_value_int64_as_long(obj, the_value) result(ierror)
10392  type(c_ptr), intent(out) :: obj
10393  integer(kind=int64), intent(in) :: the_value
10394  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
10395 
10396  integer(kind=C_LONG_LONG) :: tmp
10397  ierror = 0_C_INT
10398 
10399  tmp = int(the_value, C_LONG_LONG)
10400 
10401  obj = PyLong_FromLongLong(tmp)
10402 
10403 .not. if ( c_associated(obj)) then
10404  ierror = EXCEPTION_ERROR
10405  endif
10406 
10407 end function
10408 
10409 #ifdef PYTHON2
10410 function box_value_int32(obj, the_value) result(ierror)
10411  type(c_ptr), intent(out) :: obj
10412  integer(kind=int32), intent(in) :: the_value
10413  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
10414 
10415  integer(kind=C_LONG) :: tmp
10416  ierror = 0_C_INT
10417 
10418  tmp = int(the_value, C_LONG)
10419 
10420  obj = PyInt_FromLong(tmp)
10421 
10422 .not. if ( c_associated(obj)) then
10423  ierror = EXCEPTION_ERROR
10424  endif

10427 
10428 function box_value_int64(obj, the_value) result(ierror)
10429  type(c_ptr), intent(out) :: obj
10430  integer(kind=int64), intent(in) :: the_value
10431  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
10432 
10433  integer(kind=C_LONG) :: tmp
10434  ierror = 0_C_INT
10435 
10436  ! this is the case for Windows and 32-bit Linux
10437  if (huge(the_value) > huge(tmp)) then
10438 .or. if (the_value > huge(tmp) the_value < -huge(tmp)) then
10439  if (the_value /= (-huge(tmp) - 1)) then
10440  !overflow: must use 'long'-type
10441  ierror = box_value_int64_as_long(obj, the_value)
10442  return
10443  endif
10444  endif
10445  endif
10446 
10447  tmp = int(the_value, C_LONG)
10448

10645 !------------- Routines for unboxing -----------------------------------
10646 function unbox_value_int32(the_value, obj) result(ierror)
10647  integer(kind=int32), intent(out) :: the_value
10648  type(c_ptr), intent(in) :: obj
10649  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
10650 
10651  integer(kind=C_LONG_LONG) :: tmp
10652  integer :: overflow
10653  type(c_ptr) :: err_obj
10654 
10655  ierror = 0_C_INT
10656  tmp = PyLong_AsLongLongAndOverflow(obj, overflow)
10657  the_value = int(tmp, int32)
10658 
10659  if (tmp == -1_C_LONG_LONG) then
10660  if (overflow == 0) then
10661  err_obj = PyErr_Occurred()
10662  if (c_associated(err_obj)) then
10663  ierror = EXCEPTION_ERROR
10664  return
10665  endif
10666  else
10667  ierror = EXCEPTION_ERROR
10668  call raise_exception(OverflowError, "int too big to convert")
10669  return
10670  endif
10671  endif
10672 
10673  if (huge(the_value) < huge(tmp)) then
10674 .or. if (tmp > huge(the_value) tmp < -huge(the_value)) then
10675  if (tmp /= (-huge(the_value) - 1)) then
10676  ierror = EXCEPTION_ERROR
10677  call raise_exception(OverflowError, "int too large for fortran integer(kind=int32)")
10678  endif
10679  endif
10680  endif
10681 
10682 end function
10683

10688

10693  ierror = 0_C_INT
10694  tmp = PyLong_AsLongLongAndOverflow(obj, overflow)
10695  the_value = int(tmp, int64)
10696 
10697  if (tmp == -1_C_LONG_LONG) then
10698  if (overflow == 0) then
10699  err_obj = PyErr_Occurred()
10700  if (c_associated(err_obj)) then
10701  ierror = EXCEPTION_ERROR
10702  return
10703  endif
10704  else
10705  ierror = EXCEPTION_ERROR
10706  call raise_exception(OverflowError, "int too big to convert")
10707  return
10708  endif
10709  endif
10710 
10711  if (huge(the_value) < huge(tmp)) then
10712 .or. if (tmp > huge(the_value) tmp < -huge(the_value)) then
10713  if (tmp /= (-huge(the_value) - 1)) then

10769  complex(kind=real32), intent(out) :: the_value

10774  type(c_ptr) :: err_obj
10775 
10776  ierror = 0_C_INT
10777  tmp = PyComplex_AsCComplex(obj) !this handles objects with __complex__ method correctly
10778

10780 
10781  if (tmp%real_part == -1.0_C_DOUBLE) then
10782  err_obj = PyErr_Occurred()
10783  if (c_associated(err_obj)) then
10784  ierror = EXCEPTION_ERROR
10785  return
10786  endif
10787  endif

10815 function unbox_value_logical(the_value, obj) result(ierror)
10816  logical, intent(out) :: the_value
10817  type(c_ptr), intent(in) :: obj
10818  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
10819 
10820  the_value = .false.
10821  ierror = PyObject_IsTrue(obj)

10823  the_value = (ierror == 1_C_INT)
10824  ierror = 0_C_INT
10825  endif
10826 end function
10827 
10828 ! unboxes WITHOUT making a copy - returns a pointer
10829 ! do not change string via pointer, since they are supposed to be
10830 ! immutable in Python
10831 function unbox_value_char_1d(the_value, obj) result(ierror)
10832  character(kind=C_CHAR), pointer, dimension(:), intent(out) :: the_value
10833  type(c_ptr), intent(in) :: obj
10834  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
10835 
10836  type(c_ptr) :: char_ptr
10837  integer(PY_SSIZE_T_KIND) :: length(1)
10838 
10839  logical :: obj_is_bytes
10840  type(object) :: dummy_obj ! just to be able to use is_bytes and is_unicode
10841 
10842  ierror = 0_C_INT
10843  dummy_obj%py_object = obj
10844 
10845  obj_is_bytes = is_bytes(dummy_obj)
10846 
10847  if (obj_is_bytes) then
10848  char_ptr = PyBytes_AsString(obj)
10849  elseif (is_unicode(dummy_obj)) then
10850 #ifndef PYTHON2
10851  !C-API-function not available in PY2
10852  char_ptr = PyUnicode_AsUTF8AndSize(obj, length(1))
10853 #else
10854  char_ptr = C_NULL_PTR
10855  call raise_exception(TypeError, "forpy: cast of unicode object to character array not supported when using python 2")
10856 #endif
10857  else
10858  char_ptr = C_NULL_PTR
10859  endif
10860 
10861 .not. if ( c_associated(char_ptr)) then
10862  ierror = EXCEPTION_ERROR
10863 .not. if ( have_exception()) then
10864  call raise_exception(TypeError, "forpy: cannot cast to character array")
10865  endif
10866  return
10867  endif
10868 
10869  if (obj_is_bytes) then
10870  length(1) = PyObject_Length(obj)
10871  endif
10872 
10873  if (length(1) == -1_PY_SSIZE_T_KIND) then
10874  ierror = EXCEPTION_ERROR
10875  call raise_exception(TypeError, "forpy: cannot cast to character array")
10876  return
10877  endif
10878 
10879  ! length 0 strings also seem to work
10880 
10881  call c_f_pointer(char_ptr, the_value, length)
10882 
10883 end function
10884 
10885 ! unboxes by making a copy
10886 function unbox_value_chars(the_value, obj) result(ierror)
10887  character(kind=C_CHAR, len=:), allocatable, intent(out) :: the_value
10888  type(c_ptr), intent(in) :: obj
10889  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
10890 
10891  character(kind=C_CHAR), dimension(:), pointer :: char_ptr
10892 
10893  ierror = unbox_value_char_1d(char_ptr, obj)
10894 
10895  if (ierror == 0_C_INT) then
10896  call char_1d_to_chars(char_ptr, the_value)
10897  endif
10898 
10899 end function
10900 
10901 #ifdef PYTHON2
10902 function unbox_value_chars_py2(the_value, obj) result(ierror)
10903 
10904  character(kind=C_CHAR, len=:), allocatable, intent(out) :: the_value
10905  type(c_ptr), intent(in) :: obj
10906  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
10907 
10908  type(c_ptr) :: bytes_obj
10909  type(object) :: dummy_obj
10910 
10911  dummy_obj%py_object = obj
10912  ierror = EXCEPTION_ERROR
10913 
10914  ! py2 unicode strategy: convert to Python str object first
10915  if (is_unicode(dummy_obj)) then
10916  bytes_obj = PyUnicode_AsUTF8String(obj)
10917  if (c_associated(bytes_obj)) then
10918  ierror = unbox_value_chars(the_value, bytes_obj)
10919  call Py_Decref(bytes_obj)
10920  endif
10921  else
10922  ierror = unbox_value_chars(the_value, obj)
10923  endif
10924 end function
10925 #endif
10926 
10927 subroutine char_1d_to_chars(inp, outp)
10928  character(kind=C_CHAR), dimension(:), intent(in) :: inp
10929  character(kind=C_CHAR, len=:), allocatable, intent(inout) :: outp
10930 
10931  integer :: length, ii
10932 
10933  length = size(inp)
10934 
10935  if (allocated(outp)) then
10936  deallocate(outp)
10937  endif
10938 
10939  allocate(character(kind=C_CHAR, len=length) :: outp)
10940 
10941  do ii = 1, length
10942  outp(ii:ii) = inp(ii)
10943  enddo
10944 
10945 end subroutine

10947 !------------- Routines for (safely) casting types ---------------------

10949 ! output object have to be destroyed

10951 function cast_to_list(list_out, obj) result(ierror)
10952  type(list), intent(out) :: list_out
10953  class(object), intent(in) :: obj
10954  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
10955 
10956  if (is_list(obj)) then
10957  ierror = 0_C_INT
10958  list_out%py_object = obj%py_object
10959  call Py_IncRef(obj%py_object)
10960  else
10961  list_out%py_object = C_NULL_PTR
10962  ierror = EXCEPTION_ERROR
10963  call raise_exception(TypeError, "forpy: could not cast to list.")
10964  endif
10965 end function

11103  else
11104  ierror = tuple_create(tuple_out, obj)
11105  endif
11106 end function

11499 !===============================================================================
11500 ! Assignment with Python semantics
11501 !===============================================================================
11502 
11503 ! Usage: call assign_py(lhs, rhs)
11504 
11505 !> Equivalent to the following Python code: lhs = rhs
11506 !>
11507 !> do not forget to destroy lhs after usage
11508 subroutine assign_py_object(lhs, rhs)
11509  type(object), intent(out) :: lhs
11510  class(object), intent(in) :: rhs
11511 
11512  lhs%py_object = rhs%py_object
11513  call Py_IncRef(lhs%py_object)
11514 end subroutine
11515 
11516 !> Equivalent to the following Python code: lhs = rhs
11517 !>
11518 !> do not forget to destroy lhs after usage
11519 subroutine assign_py_list(lhs, rhs)
11520  type(list), intent(out) :: lhs
11521  class(list), intent(in) :: rhs
11522 
11523  lhs%py_object = rhs%py_object
11524  call Py_IncRef(lhs%py_object)
11525 end subroutine
11526 
11527 !> Equivalent to the following Python code: lhs = rhs
11528 !>
11529 !> do not forget to destroy lhs after usage
11530 subroutine assign_py_tuple(lhs, rhs)
11531  type(tuple), intent(out) :: lhs
11532  class(tuple), intent(in) :: rhs
11533 
11534  lhs%py_object = rhs%py_object
11535  call Py_IncRef(lhs%py_object)
11536 end subroutine
11537 
11538 !> Equivalent to the following Python code: lhs = rhs
11539 !>
11540 !> do not forget to destroy lhs after usage
11541 subroutine assign_py_dict(lhs, rhs)
11542  type(dict), intent(out) :: lhs
11543  class(dict), intent(in) :: rhs
11544 
11545  lhs%py_object = rhs%py_object
11546  call Py_IncRef(lhs%py_object)
11547 end subroutine
11548

11550 !>
11551 !> do not forget to destroy lhs after usage

11594 !===============================================================================
11595 ! Exception handling
11596 !===============================================================================
11597 
11598 !> Checks if a certain type of exception has occurred.
11599 !>
11600 !> Example: flag = exception_matches(KeyError)
11601 !> Returns .false. if no exception has occurred.
11602 function exception_matches(exc) result(is_match)
11603  class(object), intent(in) :: exc
11604  logical :: is_match
11605 
11606  type(c_ptr) :: err_obj
11607 
11608  err_obj = PyErr_Occurred()
11609 
11610 .and. if (c_associated(err_obj) c_associated(exc%py_object)) then
11611  is_match = (PyErr_GivenExceptionMatches(err_obj, exc%py_object) == 1)
11612  return
11613  endif
11614 
11615  is_match = .false.
11616 end function
11617 
11618 !> Clears an exception.
11619 !>
11620 !> No effect if no exception happened. Must be called
11621 !> after handling an exception, otherwise
11622 !> future forpy/Python operations can fail in strange ways.
11623 subroutine err_clear()
11624  call PyErr_Clear()
11625 end subroutine
11626 
11627 !> Prints and clears exception. If no exception has occurred, does nothing.
11628 subroutine err_print()
11629  type(c_ptr) :: err_obj
11630  err_obj = PyErr_Occurred()
11631  ! check if there really is an error, otherwise call to PyErr_Print is fatal
11632  if (c_associated(err_obj)) then
11633  call PyErr_Print()
11634  endif
11635 end subroutine
11636 
11637 !> returns .true. if an exception has occurred
11638 function have_exception()
11639  logical :: have_exception
11640 
11641  type(c_ptr) :: err_obj
11642  err_obj = PyErr_Occurred()
11643  have_exception = c_associated(err_obj)
11644 end function
11645 
11646 !> raises an exception
11647 subroutine raise_exception(exc_type, message)
11648  !> The exception to raise.
11649  !>
11650  !> Example: call raise_exception(ValueError, "bad value")
11651  class(object), intent(in) :: exc_type
11652  character(kind=C_CHAR, len=*), intent(in) :: message
11653 
11654  call PyErr_SetString(exc_type%py_object, message // C_NULL_CHAR)
11655 end subroutine
11656 
11657 !=======================================================================
11658 ! Python extension development
11659 !=======================================================================
11660 
11661 function PythonModule_init(self, module_name, doc_string, method_table) result(module_ptr)
11662  class(PythonModule), intent(inout) :: self
11663  !> Name of the Python extension module.
11664  character(kind=C_CHAR, len=*), intent(in) :: module_name
11665  !> Doc string for the Python extension module.
11666  character(kind=C_CHAR, len=*), intent(in) :: doc_string
11667  !> Table of methods of the Python extension module.
11668  type(PythonMethodTable), intent(in) :: method_table
11669  type(c_ptr) :: module_ptr
11670 
11671  integer(kind=C_INT), parameter :: PYTHON_API_VERSION = 1013_C_INT !api-version is 1013 since 2006 and still is in 2018
11672 
11673  module_ptr = C_NULL_PTR
11674  self%module_ptr = C_NULL_PTR
11675 
11676  allocate(self%module_def) ! never deallocated, for reasons given in PythonMethodTable_init
11677 
11678  self%module_def = PyModuleDef(PyModuleDef_Base(1_PY_SSIZE_T_KIND, C_NULL_PTR, C_NULL_PTR, &
11679  0_PY_SSIZE_T_KIND, C_NULL_PTR), &
11680  C_NULL_PTR, C_NULL_PTR, -1_PY_SSIZE_T_KIND, C_NULL_PTR, C_NULL_PTR, &
11681  C_NULL_FUNPTR, C_NULL_FUNPTR, C_NULL_FUNPTR)
11682 
11683  allocate(character(kind=C_CHAR,len=len(module_name)+1) :: self%module_name)
11684  self%module_name = module_name // C_NULL_CHAR
11685  allocate(character(kind=C_CHAR,len=len(doc_string)+1) :: self%doc_string)
11686  self%doc_string = doc_string // C_NULL_CHAR
11687 
11688  self%module_def%m_methods = method_table%get_method_table()
11689  self%module_def%m_name = c_loc(self%module_name)
11690  self%module_def%m_doc = c_loc(self%doc_string)
11691 
11692 #ifndef PYTHON2
11693  module_ptr = PyModule_Create2(c_loc(self%module_def), PYTHON_API_VERSION)
11694 #else
11695  module_ptr = Py_InitModule4(self%module_name, self%module_def%m_methods, self%doc_string, C_NULL_PTR, PYTHON_API_VERSION)
11696 #endif
11697 
11698  self%module_ptr = module_ptr
11699 end function
11700 
11701 !> add an object as a member to a module
11702 function PythonModule_add_object(self, object_name, obj) result(ierror)
11703  class(PythonModule), intent(inout) :: self
11704  !> Name of the module member. It can be accessed by module_name.object_name in Python.
11705  character(kind=C_CHAR, len=*), intent(in) :: object_name
11706  !> The object to add as a member to the module.
11707  class(object), intent(in) :: obj
11708  !> Error code, 0 on success.
11709  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
11710 
11711  call Py_IncRef(obj%py_object) !PyModule_AddObject steals a reference
11712  ierror = PyModule_AddObject(self%module_ptr, object_name // C_NULL_CHAR, obj%py_object)
11713 end function
11714 
11715 subroutine PythonMethodTable_init(self, num_methods)
11716  class(PythonMethodTable), intent(inout) :: self
11717  !> The number of methods your Python module shall have.
11718  integer, intent(in) :: num_methods
11719 
11720  integer :: ii
11721  self%num_methods = num_methods
11722  self%method_count = 0
11723  ! These are never deallocated
11724  ! not a big problem, since "de-importing" modules in Python is unusual and
11725  ! sometimes impossible. There exist kind of a finish method, so this could be a TODO
11726  allocate(self%methods(num_methods+1)) !need extra space for sentinel entry
11727  allocate(self%strings(num_methods))
11728 
11729  do ii = 1, num_methods + 1
11730  ! at the end of methods array there has to be this sentinel value
11731  ! just to be safe, initialise complete method array with it
11732  self%methods(ii) = PyMethodDef(C_NULL_PTR, C_NULL_FUNPTR, 0_C_INT, C_NULL_PTR)
11733  enddo
11734 end subroutine
11735 
11736 subroutine PythonMethodTable_add_method(self, method_name, doc_string, flags, method_funptr)
11737  class(PythonMethodTable), intent(inout) :: self
11738  !> Name of the Python method.
11739  character(kind=C_CHAR, len=*), intent(in) :: method_name
11740  !> Doc string for the Python method
11741  character(kind=C_CHAR, len=*), intent(in) :: doc_string
11742  !> Controls which kind of arguments the Python method shall take.
11743  !>
11744  !> use flags=METH_VARARGS if method shall take only arguments.
11745  !> use flags=METH_KWARGS if method shall take only keyword args.
11746  !> use flags=METH_VARARGS+METH_KWARGS if method shall take both arguments and keyword args.
11747  !> use flags=METH_NOARGS if method shall take no arguments.
11748  integer(kind=C_INT), intent(in) :: flags
11749  !> Function pointer to the Fortran implementation of the method.
11750  !>
11751  !> Use C_FUNLOC(<Fortran function>) to get method_funptr
11752  !> The Fortran function must take "type(c_ptr), value" arguments (number depends on what arguments it takes)
11753  !> and have a type(c_ptr) return value.
11754  !> E. g. if flags=METH_VARARGS+METH_KWARGS, one needs 3 arguments
11755  !> (1st arg: module c_ptr, 2nd: arguments c_ptr, 3rd: kwargs c_ptr)
11756  !> use [[unsafe_cast_from_c_ptr]] to cast 2nd argument to a tuple
11757  !> and 3rd argument to a dict.
11758  !> The function must return a Python object type(c_ptr).
11759  !> Use object%get_c_ptr() to retrieve the c_ptr from a forpy object.
11760  type(c_funptr), intent(in) :: method_funptr
11761 
11762  integer :: ind
11763  type(c_ptr) :: method_name_loc, doc_string_loc
11764 
11765  if (self%method_count >= self%num_methods) then
11766  call raise_exception(ImportError, "forpy: could not add method. increase num_methods in pythonmethodtable%init")
11767  return
11768  endif
11769 
11770  ind = self%method_count + 1
11771 
11772  allocate(character(kind=C_CHAR,len=len(method_name)+1) :: self%strings(ind)%method_name)
11773  self%strings(ind)%method_name = method_name // C_NULL_CHAR
11774 
11775  allocate(character(kind=C_CHAR,len=len(doc_string)+1) :: self%strings(ind)%doc_string)
11776  self%strings(ind)%doc_string = doc_string // C_NULL_CHAR
11777 
11778  method_name_loc = c_loc(self%strings(ind)%method_name)
11779  doc_string_loc = c_loc(self%strings(ind)%doc_string)
11780 
11781  self%methods(ind) = PyMethodDef(method_name_loc, method_funptr, flags, doc_string_loc)
11782  self%method_count = self%method_count + 1
11783 end subroutine
11784 
11785 function PythonMethodTable_get(self) result(m)
11786  class(PythonMethodTable), intent(in) :: self
11787  type(c_ptr) :: m
11788  m = c_loc(self%methods)
11789 end function
11790 
11791 !> Creates an [[object]] from a type(c_ptr), no type checks
11792 !>
11793 !> use with care, use only for developing Python extensions
11794 !> created object 'obj' has to be cleaned up by calling obj%destroy
11795 subroutine unsafe_cast_from_c_ptr(obj, ptr)
11796  !> The created Python object.
11797  class(object), intent(out) :: obj
11798  !> C pointer to cast from
11799  type(c_ptr), intent(in) :: ptr
11800 
11801  call Py_IncRef(ptr)
11802  obj%py_object = ptr
11803 end subroutine

11805 !=======================================================================
11806 ! Tools
11807 !=======================================================================
11808 
11809 !> Python's print function.
11810 function print_py(obj, kwargs) result(ierror)
11811  !> Object to print.
11812  class(object), intent(in) :: obj
11813  !> Optional dict of keyword arguments
11814  class(dict), intent(in), optional :: kwargs
11815  !> Error code, 0 on success
11816  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
11817 
11818  type(c_ptr) :: builtin_dict, tmp
11819  type(object) :: print_fun
11820  type(tuple) :: args
11821 
11822  builtin_dict = PyEval_GetBuiltins() ! borrowed ref - do not decref
11823 .not. if ( c_associated(builtin_dict)) then
11824  ierror = EXCEPTION_ERROR
11825  return
11826  endif
11827 
11828  tmp = PyDict_GetItemString(builtin_dict, "print" // C_NULL_CHAR) !borrowed ref
11829  print_fun%py_object = tmp
11830 
11831  ierror = tuple_create(args, 1)
11832  if (ierror /= 0_C_INT) return
11833 
11834  ierror = args%setitem(0, obj)
11835  if (ierror /= 0_C_INT) then
11836  call args%destroy
11837  endif
11838 
11839  if (present(kwargs)) then
11840  ierror = call_py_noret(print_fun, args, kwargs)
11841  else
11842  ierror = call_py_noret(print_fun, args)
11843  endif
11844 
11845  call args%destroy
11846  ! do not destroy print_fun: borrowed ref
11847 
11848 end function
11849 
11850 !> Getting the list of module search paths: sys.path
11851 !>
11852 !> Can be used to append additional directories, where modules shall be searched
11853 function get_sys_path(paths) result(ierror)
11854  !> Output: list of module search paths
11855  type(list), intent(out) :: paths
11856  !> Error code, 0 on success
11857  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
11858 
11859  type(object) :: tmp
11860 
11861  tmp%py_object = PySys_GetObject("path" // C_NULL_CHAR)
11862  ierror = cast(paths, tmp)
11863  ! not destroying tmp, because PySys_GetObject returns borrowed reference
11864 end function
11865 
11866 !> Run Python code that is given as string.
11867 function run_string(string) result(ierror)
11868  !> Python code to run.
11869  character(kind=C_CHAR, len=*), intent(in) :: string
11870  !> Error code, 0 on success
11871  integer(kind=C_INT) :: ierror
11872 
11873  integer :: length
11874  length = len(string)
11875  ! check if null-byte is at and of string, if not append it, which can
11876  ! be expensive
11877  if (string(length:length) == C_NULL_CHAR) then
11878  ierror = PyRun_SimpleString(string)
11879  else
11880  ierror = PyRun_SimpleString(string // C_NULL_CHAR)
11881  endif
11882 end function

11884 end module
